pols = read_csv("pols-month.csv") %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  mutate(mon =
  lubridate::floor_date(mon, c("month")), date = mon
  ) %>%
  select(date, everything(), -mon)

gdp = read_csv("GDP.csv") %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  mutate(date =
  lubridate::floor_date(date, c("month"))
  ) %>%
  mutate(gdp = value) %>%
  select(-value)

I have read and cleaned both the pols data and gdp data. Also, I have changed their mon/date variable to have the same name and be both dates to the first day of the month. Next, I will join the two datasets by date.

pols_gdp = left_join(pols, gdp, by = "date") %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarise(gdp_month = mean(as.numeric(gdp), na.rm = TRUE),
            prez_party = ifelse(prez_gop > 0, "republican", "democratic")) %>%
  na.omit()
## Warning in mean(as.numeric(gdp), na.rm = TRUE): NAs introduced by coercion

## Warning in mean(as.numeric(gdp), na.rm = TRUE): NAs introduced by coercion

## Warning in mean(as.numeric(gdp), na.rm = TRUE): NAs introduced by coercion

## Warning in mean(as.numeric(gdp), na.rm = TRUE): NAs introduced by coercion
pols_gdp %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = gdp_month)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = prez_party)) +
  geom_line()

Above graph shows the GDP of U.S. in 1948-01-01, 2015-01-01, including the party of the president during those period (red dots indicating a democratic president and blue dots indicating a republican president).
